erritory, and monarchs alike. Anna Grzymała-Busse demonstrates how the church shaped distinct aspects of the European state. Conflicts with the papacy fragmented territorial authority in Europe for centuries to come, propagating urban autonomy and ideas of sovereignty. Thanks to its organizational advantages and human capital, the church also developed the institutional precedents adopted by rulers across Europe—from chanceries and taxation to courts and councils. Church innovations made possible both the rule of law and parliamentary representation.Bringing to light a wealth of historical evidence about papal conflict, excommunications, and ecclesiastical institutions, Sacred Foundations reveals how the challenge and example of powerful religious authorities gave rise to secular state institutions and galvanized state capacity.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aChurch and state-History-Europe. 7aHISTORY / Medieval.2bisacsh  a14th century.  aAdversarial system.  aArbitration award.  aArchbishop of Canterbury.  aArchdeacon.  aAudit.  aBenefice.  aCanon law (Catholic Church).  aCapitalism.  aCatholic Church in England and Wales.  aClergy.  aCommercial Revolution.  aCommon Pool.  aConsent.  aControl variable.  aCriminal law.  aDebtor.  aDoctrine.  aDonation of Constantine.  aDummy variable (statistics).  aEnthusiasm.  aExchequer.  aExcommunication.  aExpenditure.  aFisc.  aForms of government.  aFriar.  aHoly Roman Empire.  aHuman capital.  aHussite Wars.  aInstitution.  aInterdependence.  aInvestiture Controversy.  aJurisdiction.  aJurist.  aLanguage.  aLanguedoc.  aLawyer.  aLump sum.  aMagnanimity.  aMerciless Parliament.  aMoneyer.  aPacta sunt servanda.  aPawnbroker.  aPope Gregory IX.  aPope.  aPopularity.  aPrecedent.  